The network chosen for this assignment consist in a human brain functional interactions network. Nodes are regions covering the whole human brain while edges are weighted by the Jaccard index between patterns of activation across experiments.

Analyze the network by answer the following questions:

1. What is the number of nodes and links?

data <- readMat("Coactivation_matrix.mat")
matrix <- as.matrix(data$Coactivation.matrix) 
g <- graph.adjacency(matrix, mode="undirected", weighted=TRUE)

After having created the graph of the network from the available matlab Coactivaction Matrix, by using the functions vcount() and ecount() we can learn that the networks is made by 638 nodes and 18625 edges.

vcount(g)
## [1] 638
ecount(g)
## [1] 18625

2. What is the average degree in the network? And the standard deviation of the degree?

mean(degree(g))
## [1] 58.38558
sd(degree(g))
## [1] 33.74145

3. Plot the degree distribution in linear-linear scale and in log-log-scale. What is the degree of the most connected node?

par(mfrow=c(2,1))
plot(degree_distribution(g, cumulative=T),type="s", main="Degree Distribution (linear scale)")
plot(log(1:180),log(degree_distribution(g, cumulative=T)), type="s", main="Degree Distribution (log scale)")

which.max(degree(g))
## [1] 331
max(degree(g))
## [1] 179

The highest degree in the network is 179 belonging to node 331.

4. What is the clustering coefficient (transitivity) in the network?

transitivity(g)
## [1] 0.4100847

5. What is the assortativity (degree) in the network?

assortativity_degree(g)
## [1] 0.3761221

The Pearson coefficient gives a positive value, meaning that the correlation between nodes is positive; thus nodes of similar degree tends to be connected to each other.

6. Using the Louvain method, does the network have a community structure? If so, what is its modularity?

commUW<- cluster_louvain(g,weights=NULL)
comm<- cluster_louvain(g,weights=E(g)$value)
sizes(comm)
## Community sizes
##   1   2   3   4   5 
## 116 113 219 112  78
modularity(comm,weights=E(g)$value)
## [1] 0.4674459

The cluster louvain algorithm found 5 communities and the resulting modularity is equal to 0.467.

7. Test that the clustering coefficient in the network cannot be statistically explained by a configuration model in which the nodes have the same degree as the original.

par(mfrow=c(1,2),mar=c(0, 0, 0, 0))
model1 <- erdos.renyi.game(vcount(g),p.or.m=ecount(g),type="gnm")
plot(g);plot(model1)

From the graphical comparison we can learn a wide difference between the real network and the Erdos Reny implemented with the number of nodes and edges of the original.

c(mean(degree(g)),mean(degree(model1)))
## [1] 58.38558 58.38558
plot(degree_distribution(g,cum=T),type="s",log="xy", lwd=2)
lines(degree_distribution(model1,cum=T),col="red")

As one would expect the average degrees of the two networks are the same, however the degree distribution are different, with the a more rapid decrease in the artificial one.

c(diameter(g), diameter(model1))
## [1] 0.1574314 3.0000000
c(transitivity(g), transitivity(model1))
## [1] 0.41008471 0.09112096
c(assortativity_degree(g), assortativity_degree(model1))
## [1]  0.3761221303 -0.0001641224

Consequently the metrics are also different; in particular the assortativity degree of the Erdos Reny network is negative.

comm0 <- cluster_fast_greedy(g)
comm1 <- cluster_fast_greedy(model1)
compare(comm1,comm0,method="nmi")
## [1] 0.004629859

Lastly, the clustering algorithm detects a difference while building communities from the two networks.
